    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.EditDiskConfirmTitle">Edit Disk</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.EditDiskConfirmBody">Edit {0} ({1})?&#x0a;&#x0a;The disk will be unmounted and remounted with the new settings. All data currently in memory will be lost.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.TempDirWillBeReset">This disk is currently your Windows Temp directory. It will be automatically reset to the system default before unmounting.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.ExitTempDirWillBeReset">Your Windows Temp directory is currently set to a RAM disk. It will be automatically reset to the system default before exiting.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.TrayExitTempResetTitle">Temp Directory on RAM Disk</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.TrayExitTempResetBody">Your Windows Temp directory is set to a RAM disk. It will become inaccessible after the disk is unmounted.&#x0a;&#x0a;Reset Temp to the system default and exit?</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.ResetTempConfirmTitle">Reset Temp Directories</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.ResetTempConfirmBody">This will restore TEMP and TMP to their Windows default:&#x0a;&#x0a;  %USERPROFILE%\AppData\Local\Temp&#x0a;&#x0a;Continue?</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.ResetTempSuccess">TEMP and TMP have been reset to their Windows defaults.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.ResetTempFailed">Failed to reset temp directories.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.SetTempDirSuccess">TEMP and TMP have been set to:&#x0a;&#x0a;  {0}</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.SetTempDirFailed">Failed to set temp directory.</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.SetTempDirWarningTitle">RAM Disk as Temp — Compatibility Warning</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.SetTempDirWarningBody">Setting TEMP to a RAM disk may cause certain installers to fail when they try to run from this path. Known examples include WeChatWin_*.exe and other packages that are extracted to TEMP and launched by a system-level service.&#x0a;&#x0a;This happens because WinFsp drives are only visible within the current user session. If an installer is executed by a system-level process (such as the Windows Package Manager service), it cannot access user-session drive letters.&#x0a;&#x0a;Not all winget packages are affected — many install without issue.&#x0a;&#x0a;Do you want to continue?</sys:String>
    <sys:String x:Key="Msg.StartupTempAutoMountWarning">Your Windows Temp directory is set to a RAM disk ({0}).&#x0a;&#x0a;Some installers — such as WeChatWin_*.exe — may fail when extracted to this path and run by a system-level process. Not all packages are affected.&#x0a;&#x0a;You can restore the default Temp directory from the toolbar if you encounter installation errors.</sys:String>

